where <italic>E</italic><sub>assigned</sub> is the <italic>E</italic>-value obtained from the assigned clade; <italic>E</italic><sub>alternative</sub> is the <italic>E</italic>-value that is the smallest one among the rest of the clades. Thus, a lower <italic>Q</italic> implies that the assigned clade is more significant. Two elements in the training set are weakly assigned (<italic>Q</italic> &gt; 10<sup>−3</sup>), whereas the other elements are reliably assigned (<italic>Q</italic> &lt; 10<sup>−10</sup>) (<ext-link ext-link-type="uri" xlink:href="http://nar.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/content/full/gkp752/DC1">Supplementary Table S2</ext-link>). Our program reports the <italic>Q-</italic>value for all identified elements, to provide significance estimations for the predicted clade.
